<!--
Swiss German (de-CH) translation вҖ” Schweizer Hochdeutsch. Full UI
coverage. Du-form throughout, intimate / spousal register matching the
existing insight prose. No Sie-form anywhere. Brand name "ClothesCast"
stays verbatim.

Swiss Hochdeutsch differs from German Standard German in three ways
that surface in this app's strings:

- **No Гҹ.** Swiss orthography replaced Гҹ with ss decades ago, so
  "heiГҹ" вҶ’ "heiss" is mandatory throughout. (That's the only Гҹ in
  the whole file вҖ” most of the German UI lands in Гҹ-free vocabulary,
  lucky for us.)
- **В«вҖҰВ» guillemets** instead of вҖһвҖҰвҖң for nested quotes inside the
  prose descriptions (e.g. settings_tonight_description quoting the
  toggle label). Swiss editorial convention follows French
  typographic practice here; the German low-high pair reads as
  imported German press style.
- **"Natel-Sprache"** for what de-DE / de-AT call "Telefon-" or
  "Handy-Sprache". "Natel" is the historical Swisscom-coined Swiss
  term for a mobile phone and is the register a Swiss reader expects
  in formal app copy; "Handy" is understood but reads as imported
  German.

Other well-known Helvetisms (Velo, Tram, Trottoir, Coiffeur,
parkieren, Billett) are transport / household terms that don't
surface in a weather-and-clothes app's UI, so the rest of the file
is byte-identical to values-de.

What is NOT overridden, by design:
- `app_name` вҖ” brand identifier, identical across locales.
- `insight_time_am` / `_pm` / `_midnight` / `_noon` (and the *_minutes
  variants) вҖ” English-only spoken-time formatter helpers. German
  locales use `insight_time_hour` / `insight_time_hour_minutes`
  ("15 Uhr" / "15 Uhr 30") which are translated below; the AM/PM keys
  exist for `Locale.language == "en"` paths only and would never be
  read in a German runtime.

Picker labels under `settings_region_language_*` and
`settings_tts_voice_locale_*` give the German names for every offered
locale (Englisch (Vereinigte Staaten), FranzГ¶sisch (Kanada), Chinesisch
(vereinfacht), вҖҰ). The locale tag stored on disk (en-US / fr-CA /
zh-CN) is unchanged; only the displayed label localizes.
-->
